Perfect â€” this is the right moment to be very explicit and mechanical.
Below is a production-safe, Talos-compatible, OIDC-compatible way to join spokes â†’ hub using Submariner OSS, assuming:

âœ… Broker already installed in HUB
âœ… You are using Talos OS
âœ… Omni / OIDC is enabled (humans use OIDC)
âœ… Submariner must run in-cluster (not from your laptop)

Weâ€™ll do this in clear phases, with exact files and commands.

PHASE 0 â€” What we are building (mental map)

For each SPOKE cluster we will:

Create a ServiceAccount (machine auth)

Create a short-lived token

Build a minimal kubeconfig (NO OIDC)

Store it as a Secret in the HUB

Run a Job in the HUB that executes subctl join

Verify gateways + connectivity

Talos does nothing special here.

PHASE 1 â€” On EACH SPOKE cluster (once per spoke)

These commands are run against the SPOKE cluster API
(from a VM that can reach it, or via Omni exec)

1ï¸âƒ£ Create namespace
kubectl create namespace submariner-operator

2ï¸âƒ£ Create ServiceAccount
kubectl -n submariner-operator create serviceaccount submariner-bootstrap

3ï¸âƒ£ Bind cluster-admin (required by subctl)
# submariner-bootstrap-crb.yaml
apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: ClusterRoleBinding
metadata:
  name: submariner-bootstrap
roleRef:
  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io
  kind: ClusterRole
  name: cluster-admin
subjects:
- kind: ServiceAccount
  name: submariner-bootstrap
  namespace: submariner-operator

kubectl apply -f submariner-bootstrap-crb.yaml


âš ï¸ Yes, cluster-admin is required during install.
You can reduce permissions later.

4ï¸âƒ£ Generate a token (THIS IS CRITICAL)
kubectl -n submariner-operator create token submariner-bootstrap


You should see something like:

eyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6...


ğŸ‘‰ Save this token (copy it somewhere safe)

5ï¸âƒ£ Get the SPOKE API server URL
kubectl config view --raw -o jsonpath='{.clusters[0].cluster.server}'


Example:

https://10.0.0.10:6443

6ï¸âƒ£ Get the CA certificate (Talos-safe way)

Talos does NOT embed CA in kubeconfig when using OIDC.

Use this instead:

kubectl -n kube-system get configmap kube-root-ca.crt \
  -o jsonpath='{.data.ca\.crt}' > ca.crt


Then base64 it:

base64 -w0 ca.crt


Save the output â€” this is your certificate-authority-data.

7ï¸âƒ£ Create the SPOKE kubeconfig (FILE 1)

ğŸ“„ spoke1.kubeconfig

apiVersion: v1
kind: Config
clusters:
- name: spoke1
  cluster:
    server: https://<SPOKE_API>:6443
    certificate-authority-data: <BASE64_CA>
contexts:
- name: spoke1
  context:
    cluster: spoke1
    user: submariner-bootstrap
current-context: spoke1
users:
- name: submariner-bootstrap
  user:
    token: <TOKEN_FROM_STEP_4>


â— Replace:

<SPOKE_API>

<BASE64_CA>

<TOKEN_FROM_STEP_4>

8ï¸âƒ£ Validate kubeconfig (VERY IMPORTANT)
kubectl --kubeconfig=spoke1.kubeconfig get nodes


If this fails â†’ STOP and fix it.
Submariner will NOT work if this fails.

PHASE 2 â€” Move kubeconfig into the HUB cluster

These commands run against the HUB cluster

9ï¸âƒ£ Create Secret in HUB
kubectl -n submariner-k8s-broker create secret generic spoke1-kubeconfig \
  --from-file=kubeconfig=spoke1.kubeconfig


Verify:

kubectl -n submariner-k8s-broker get secret spoke1-kubeconfig

PHASE 3 â€” Run subctl JOIN as a Job (HUB)

This avoids laptop / OIDC / Talos issues.

ğŸ”Ÿ Create the JOIN Job (FILE 2)

ğŸ“„ subctl-join-spoke1.yaml

apiVersion: batch/v1
kind: Job
metadata:
  name: subctl-join-spoke1
  namespace: submariner-k8s-broker
spec:
  backoffLimit: 1
  template:
    spec:
      restartPolicy: Never
      containers:
      - name: subctl
        image: quay.io/submariner/subctl:0.19.1
        command:
        - /bin/sh
        - -c
        - |
          subctl join \
            --kubeconfig /spoke/kubeconfig \
            broker-info.subm \
            --clusterid spoke1 \
            --natt=true
        volumeMounts:
        - name: spoke-kubeconfig
          mountPath: /spoke
      volumes:
      - name: spoke-kubeconfig
        secret:
          secretName: spoke1-kubeconfig


--natt=true is REQUIRED because you have overlapping PodCIDRs.

1ï¸âƒ£1ï¸âƒ£ Apply the Job
kubectl apply -f subctl-join-spoke1.yaml


Watch logs:

kubectl -n submariner-k8s-broker logs job/subctl-join-spoke1 -f


You want to see:

âœ“ Cluster "spoke1" joined successfully

PHASE 4 â€” Verify Submariner is actually working
1ï¸âƒ£2ï¸âƒ£ Check gateway nodes (SPOKE)
kubectl get nodes -l submariner.io/gateway=true

1ï¸âƒ£3ï¸âƒ£ Check pods
kubectl -n submariner-operator get pods


You should see:

submariner-gateway

submariner-route-agent

submariner-operator

1ï¸âƒ£4ï¸âƒ£ Verify connection in HUB
kubectl -n submariner-k8s-broker get clusters

1ï¸âƒ£5ï¸âƒ£ Test pod-to-pod connectivity

Create a test pod in HUB and SPOKE:

kubectl run test --image=busybox -it --restart=Never -- sh


From HUB â†’ ping SPOKE pod IP.

If this works â†’ network fabric is DONE.

PHASE 5 â€” What happens next (important)

Now:

Pods can talk cross-cluster

Services can be resolved

Consul gossip works

Envoy xDS works

MeshGateways become OPTIONAL

Submariner solved L3/L4
Consul solves L7 + service discovery
Used in managed clusters

Compatible with Talos constraints
###################################################


apiVersion: batch/v1
kind: Job
metadata:
  name: subctl-join
  namespace: submariner-operator
spec:
  backoffLimit: 1
  template:
    spec:
      restartPolicy: Never
      serviceAccountName: submariner-bootstrap
      containers:
      - name: subctl
        image: quay.io/submariner/subctl:0.19.1
        command:
        - /bin/sh
        - -c
        - |
          subctl join \
            broker-info.subm \
            --clusterid spoke1 \
            --natt=true \
            --kubeconfig /var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/kubeconfig
        volumeMounts:
        - name: broker
          mountPath: /broker
      volumes:
      - name: broker
        secret:
          secretName: broker-info


